## Implementing the Extractor Yourself

### Suggested API design

For your own program, separate the extraction core from the UI.

```text
lib/
  gbcam_save.rs       # pure parsing + decoding, no CLI/UI
cli/
  main.rs             # file args, output paths, progress
app/
  Android frontend    # calls the same library logic
```

Recommended core API:

```rust
pub struct ExtractOptions {
    pub photo_directory_roll: Option<usize>,
    pub include_deleted: bool,
    pub include_empty: bool,
    pub palette: Palette,
    pub scale: u32,
}

pub struct DecodedImage {
    pub title: String,
    pub suggested_filename: String,
    pub width: u32,
    pub height: u32,
    pub rgba: Vec<u8>,
    pub display_index: Option<usize>,
    pub physical_slot: Option<usize>,
    pub offset: usize,
    pub deleted: bool,
    pub empty: bool,
}

pub fn extract_gbcam_images(data: &[u8], opts: ExtractOptions) -> Result<Vec<DecodedImage>, Error>;
```

Why this shape works well:

- CLI can write `rgba` to PNG.
- Android can show previews directly.
- Your library does not care whether the bytes came from USB, a file picker, Termux, or a cartridge reader.
- Deleted/empty state can be shown in the UI without throwing image data away.

### Preserve display order and physical slot

Do not only return image buffers. Return metadata too.

Useful metadata:

| Field | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| `display_index` | User-visible album order |
| `physical_slot` | Actual SRAM slot, useful for debugging and save editing |
| `offset` | Lets you verify with a hex editor |
| `deleted` | GUI can mark it with a red X like FlashGBX |
| `empty` | Lets you hide blank slots if desired |
| `source_kind` | `AlbumPhoto`, `GameFace`, `LastSeen` |

### Empty image detection

FlashGBX detects an empty image by SHA-1 hashing the decoded paletted image bytes:

```text
ef58a812a81ab14549d8f4fb86e9ecb54a5fb723
```

That hash is based on `img.tobytes()` from the Pillow paletted image. In your own implementation this corresponds to the raw palette-index buffer, not RGBA output.

So if you decode to palette indices first:

```text
sha1(index_buffer) == ef58a812a81ab14549d8f4fb86e9ecb54a5fb723
```

If you hash RGBA bytes instead, you will get a different hash.

### Corruption handling

Recommended behavior for your program:

| Problem | Recommended behavior |
|---|---|
| File size not `0x20000` or `0x100000` | Hard error |
| 1 MiB file without selected roll | Ask user / return `NeedsRollSelection` |
| Roll > 7 | Hard error |
| Order-table value `0xFF` | Mark physical slot as deleted |
| Order-table duplicate | Mark physical slot as deleted |
| Order-table value `>= 30` | Mark as corrupt/deleted or hard error in strict mode |
| Image block shorter than expected | Hard error |
| All images blank | Warn: likely wrong file or bad dump |

