## Technical Hardware Context

This part matters mostly if you plan to go beyond image extraction and interact with the cartridge directly.

### Game Boy Camera cartridge architecture

The Game Boy Camera cartridge contains:

- ROM
- SRAM
- MAC-GBD controller
- M64282FP “retina” image sensor

The MAC-GBD controller behaves broadly like an MBC3-style memory controller, but with camera-specific behavior.

### Memory mapping overview

| Range | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `0000-3FFF` | ROM bank 0, read-only |
| `4000-7FFF` | Switchable ROM bank |
| `A000-BFFF` | External RAM bank or camera registers |
| `0000-1FFF` write | RAM enable; `0x0A` enables SRAM writes |
| `2000-3FFF` write | ROM bank select |
| `4000-5FFF` write | RAM bank select or camera-register select |

Camera-register selection is done by writing a value with bit 5 set. Commonly bank `0x10` is used for camera registers.

### Why save extraction is simpler than capture emulation

The sensor and cartridge hardware perform capture-time processing:

- exposure timing
- gain control
- edge control
- level control
- analog comparison against dithering/contrast thresholds
- reduction to Game Boy 2bpp graphics

By the time an image is stored in SRAM, all of that is already done. Your extractor does not need to emulate the M64282FP sensor. It only needs to decode already-formed Game Boy tiles.

### Why images are 128x112

The sensor transfers `128 x 128` pixels, but the useful stored/visible image ignores the first and last 8 rows, leaving:

```text
128 x (128 - 8 - 8) = 128 x 112
```

That is why normal images decode as:

```text
16 tile columns x 14 tile rows = 128 x 112 pixels
```

### Save restoration caveat

The original Game Boy Camera documentation notes that GB Camera RAM can only be written when the Game Boy `PHI` clock pin is high. Some simple cartridge readers historically handled reads but could not reliably restore GB Camera SRAM backups.

This guide focuses on **dumping and extracting**. If you later write modified saves back to real hardware, use software and hardware known to support GB Camera save writing correctly.

